  "Homeostasis": "常态",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "这个课程涵盖了分析和总结数据集的中心的基本测量方法。 您将学会如何计算和应用平均值、 中位数和模式, 并了解何时最合适 。",
  "What is cholesterol's role in the body, and why is the distinction between LDL and HDL cholesterol important for health?": "胆固醇在身体中的作用是什么,为什么LDL和HDL胆固醇之间的区别对健康很重要?",
  "Cholesterol biochemistry: (1) Structure: a 4-ring steroid with a hydroxyl group — amphipathic molecule. (2) Cell membrane role: cholesterol inserts between phospholipids, reducing fluidity at high temperatures (restricts movement) and preventing crystallization at low temperatures — acts as a 'fluidity buffer.' About 25-30% of mammalian membrane lipids. (3) Biosynthesis: liver produces ~800 mg/day (endogenous) via the mevalonate pathway. Key enzyme: HMG-CoA reductase (target of statin drugs — lovastatin discovered by Akira Endo, 1976). Dietary cholesterol absorption varies widely (~30-70%). (4) Lipoprotein transport: Cholesterol is hydrophobic → transported in blood via lipoproteins. LDL (Low-Density Lipoprotein) — delivers cholesterol to peripheral tissues; excess LDL → oxidized LDL → taken up by macrophages → foam cells → atherosclerotic plaques → heart attack/stroke. HDL (High-Density Lipoprotein) — removes excess cholesterol from tissues via reverse cholesterol transport to liver → protective. (5) Health guidelines: optimal LDL < 100 mg/dL; HDL > 60 mg/dL (protective); total cholesterol < 200 mg/dL. (6) Precursor roles: sex hormones (estrogen, progesterone, testosterone), adrenal cortical hormones (cortisol, aldosterone), bile salts (emulsify dietary fats), vitamin D (7-dehydrocholesterol in skin → UV-B → cholecalciferol).": "胆固醇的作用:胆固醇在磷酸盐中插入,在高温(限制运动)下降低流动性,防止在低温下结晶化——作用为“溶液缓冲”。 大约25-30%的哺乳动物血浆脂。 (3) 生物合成:肝脏通过等离子体接触途径产生800毫克/日(遗传性),关键酶:HMG-CoA再生酶(Statin药物的目标——Akira Endo发现,1976年)在高温(限制运动)下降低流动性,在低温下防止结晶化——作为“溶液缓冲”。",
  "What is bioluminescence, and how do the biochemical reactions that produce biological light illustrate enzyme catalysis?": "什么是生物发光,产生生物光的生化反应如何说明酶催化?",
  "Bioluminescence biochemistry: (1) General reaction: Luciferin + O₂ → (luciferase catalyst, often ATP-dependent) → Oxyluciferin + Light. The terms luciferin/luciferase (from Latin 'lucifer' = light-bearer) are generic — different organisms evolved different luciferins independently. (2) Firefly (Photinus pyralis): D-luciferin + ATP + O₂ → (firefly luciferase) → oxyluciferin + AMP + PPi + CO₂ + light (λ 560 nm, yellow-green). Quantum yield ~0.88 (88% of reactions produce a photon — among the most efficient chemical reactions known). Used for mating signals. (3) Marine bioluminescence: coelenterazine is the most common marine luciferin (jellyfish Aequorea victoria uses it — source of GFP, Green Fluorescent Protein: Shimomura discovered aequorin, Chalfie & Tsien engineered GFP — Nobel 2008). Deep-sea anglerfish use symbiotic bioluminescent bacteria (Photobacterium). ~76% of deep-sea organisms are bioluminescent. (4) Applications: GFP revolutionized cell biology (gene expression reporter, protein localization tracking). ATP-dependent luciferase used as biosensor for contamination detection (ATP = indicator of living cells). Bioluminescence imaging in cancer research (tumor monitoring in mice). (5) Evolution: bioluminescence evolved independently at least 40-50 times across diverse taxa — bacteria, dinoflagellates, fungi, jellyfish, corals, insects, fish, squid.": "生物光度生物化学:(1) 常规反应: Lufiferin + O2 + o2 + (luciferase 催化剂,经常依赖ATP) = 氧基硫酸酯 + 光 。Luciferin/luciferase (拉丁语“lucifer” = 光携带者 ) 是通用的—— 不同的生物体进化了不同的润滑素。 (2) 火焰(Photinus pylamilis): D-luciferin + ATP + O2 蛋白质变异性 + (Flair luciferase) + 氧基素变异性 + APPi + CO2 + 光( 560 nm, 黄绿色绿色绿色绿色绿色) 。 Qualtuum 产值 ~0.88(8 % 反应产生光度,这是已知的最有效化学反应 。 用于交配方信号。 (3) 海洋生物光层光度: 红蛋白色红蛋白质变异变异生物变异性(雌白亚利用GFD) 生物变异生物变异性生物变变变异性生物变异性生物变异性生物变异性生物变异性) 数据 。",
  "What are antioxidants, and how do they protect cells from damage caused by free radicals?": "什么是抗氧化剂,它们如何保护细胞不受自由基造成的破坏?",
  "Antioxidants and oxidative stress: (1) Free radicals: atoms or molecules with unpaired electrons — highly reactive. Reactive oxygen species (ROS): superoxide (O₂⁻•), hydroxyl radical (•OH), hydrogen peroxide (H₂O₂), singlet oxygen. Generated by: mitochondrial electron transport chain (1-3% of O₂ becomes superoxide normally), UV radiation, ionizing radiation, cigarette smoke, pollution, some drugs. (2) Damage mechanism: lipid peroxidation (chain reaction: free radical abstracts H from unsaturated fatty acid → lipid radical → reacts with O₂ → peroxyl radical → propagates to neighboring lipids → membrane damage). Also: DNA oxidation (8-oxoguanine → G→T transversions → mutations), protein oxidation (carbonylation → loss of function, aggregation). (3) Antioxidant defense: Enzymatic — superoxide dismutase (SOD: O₂⁻• → H₂O₂), catalase (H₂O₂ → H₂O + O₂), glutathione peroxidase (reduces H₂O₂ using GSH). Non-enzymatic — vitamin C (ascorbate, water-soluble, regenerates vitamin E), vitamin E (α-tocopherol, lipid-soluble, breaks lipid peroxidation chains), glutathione (GSH, most abundant intracellular antioxidant, tripeptide), carotenoids (β-carotene, lycopene), polyphenols (from fruits, vegetables, tea, coffee). (4) Oxidative stress: imbalance between ROS production and antioxidant defense → linked to aging (free radical theory of aging — Denham Harman, 1956), cancer, cardiovascular disease, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's.": "抗氧化剂和氧化性压力:(1) 自由基: 原子或分子, 含有未受污染的维生素; 高度反应; 抗氧类(ROS): 超氧化(O2)、 氢氧基(OH)、 过氧化氢(H2O2, 单氧)。 由下列因素生成: 线球体电子运输链(O2的1%-3%通常成为超级氧化物)、 UV辐射、 电离辐射、烟雾、污染、一些药物。 (2) 破坏机制: 脂过氧化(链反应: 不饱和脂肪酸的碱性提取基性 H)、 脂基质基质(O2)、 过氧基(O2O2OH) 亚氧基亚素; 蛋白质氧化(碳酸丧失功能、营养) 脱氧基(O2O2O2, 氧基内基内基内基内基离子) ; 氧(O2O2O2, 氧基内基内基内基内基质(O2) 内基内基内基) 氧(O2O2) 内基内基内基内氧-内基内基内氧-内氧- 氧- 氧-内基) 氧(OTO内基) 氧-内基) 氧(O氧(O基内基内基内基内基内基内基内氧-内基) (碳基) 氧-内氧-内离基) (O基)",
  "A nutrition label on a packaged cookie states: 'Calories: 200, Total Fat: 10g (Saturated 3g, Trans 0g), Total Carbohydrates: 25g (Sugars 15g), Protein: 2g.' However, the ingredient list includes 'partially hydrogenated soybean oil.' A biochemistry student realizes this is misleading. Why might the label say '0g trans fat' while still containing trans fats, and how should the student evaluate this product?": "包装饼干上的一个营养标签写道 : “ 分类: 200, Total Fat: 10g (饱和 3g, Trans 0g), 碳水化合物总量: 25g (糖 15g), 蛋白质: 2g。 ”然而, 成分清单包括“ 局部氢化大豆油 。 ” 生物化学学生意识到这有误导性。 为什么标签上说“ 0g 反脂肪” , 却仍然含有反式脂肪, 学生应该如何评估这一产品?",
  "Hidden trans fats in food labeling: (1) FDA labeling loophole (pre-2018 ban, still relevant for some products): manufacturers could round down to 0g if serving contained < 0.5g trans fat. Strategy: reduce serving size to get trans fat below 0.5g → label '0g trans fat.' (2) The giveaway: 'partially hydrogenated oil' in ingredients = contains trans fats. Partial hydrogenation adds some (not all) H atoms to unsaturated fatty acids, and the process inevitably isomerizes some cis double bonds to trans configuration. Fully hydrogenated oils (all double bonds eliminated → saturated) contain no trans fats. (3) Cumulative exposure: 0.49g × 4 servings = ~2g trans fat. WHO recommends < 1% of total calories from trans fat (~2.2g for 2000 kcal diet). Even small amounts increase cardiovascular risk. (4) FDA banned partially hydrogenated oils (PHOs) from US food supply (final compliance June 2018) — but some products with extended shelf lives may still contain them, and exemptions/enforcement gaps exist. (5) Global progress: Denmark first country to effectively ban (2003, ≤ 2% of total fat). WHO REPLACE initiative targets global elimination. As of 2023, ~60 countries have implemented regulations. (6) Lesson: ingredient lists > nutrition facts labels for identifying problematic substances.": "食品标签中隐藏的跨层脂肪:(1) 林业发展局标签标签漏洞(2018年之前的禁令,对于某些产品仍然适用):如果产品中含 < 0.5g 反转脂肪,制造商可以四舍五入到0.5g 反转脂肪。战略:降低服务规模,将反转脂肪降到0.5g + 标签 ' 0g 反转脂肪。(2) 配方:成分中“部分氢化油”=含有反转脂肪。部分氢化会增加一些(不是全部)H原子至不饱和脂肪酸,而这一过程不可避免地使某些丙基双层债券异构成变性。全氢化油(所有双层债券均消除了 ) 不含反转脂肪。(3) 累积暴露:0.49g × 4 = 标签 =~ 2g 反转脂肪。世卫组织建议 < 跨脂肪总热量的1% (2000 kcal 饮食) 部分增加心血管风险。(4) 林业发展局禁止美国食品供应中的部分氢化油(PHOs) (最终遵守201818年6月) ,但一些储延长寿命的产品可能含有它们,但不含反脂肪的双重债券。 (3) 累积接触的含含脂肪。累计接触。(3) 累积暴露:0.49 = =~ =~ IMBBD 执行 20xxxxx 。",
  "A marathon runner collapses at mile 20 — the infamous 'hitting the wall.' Medical staff find she is hypoglycemic (blood glucose 52 mg/dL) and barely conscious. She had eaten only a large pasta dinner the night before and skipped breakfast. Using your knowledge of biochemistry, explain what happened metabolically and how dehydration synthesis and hydrolysis relate to energy storage and release during exercise.": "",
  "Marathon metabolism and the polymer-monomer connection: (1) Carb-loading: the pasta dinner provided glucose → dehydration synthesis stored it as glycogen (α-1,4 and α-1,6 glycosidic bonds). Muscle glycogen (~400g, ~1,600 kcal) for local use. Liver glycogen (~100g, ~400 kcal) for blood glucose maintenance. Total: ~2,000 kcal from glycogen. (2) Marathon energy demand: ~100 kcal/mile × 26.2 miles = ~2,620 kcal. At marathon pace, fuel is ~50-70% carbohydrate, ~30-50% fat (ratio depends on intensity and training). (3) Progressive fuel depletion: miles 1-10: glycogen + fat → plenty of ATP. Miles 10-18: glycogen declining, fat oxidation increasing. Mile ~20: glycogen essentially depleted ('the wall'). Fat oxidation cannot produce ATP fast enough to maintain pace (fat yields more total ATP per gram but at slower rate due to β-oxidation complexity). (4) Blood glucose crash: liver glycogen (maintained blood glucose) runs out → hypoglycemia → brain relies almost exclusively on glucose → confusion, dizziness, collapse. (5) Skipped breakfast: liver glycogen already depleted overnight (used to maintain blood glucose during sleep) → started race with ~50-60g liver glycogen instead of ~100g. (6) Hydrolysis is the key catabolic reaction: glycogen phosphorylase + debranching enzyme → glucose-1-phosphate → glucose-6-phosphate → glycolysis → pyruvate → mitochondria. (7) Prevention: sports nutrition recommends carb-loading 48-72 hours before, breakfast 3-4 hours before race, mid-race fueling (gels/drinks every 30-45 min to maintain blood glucose).": "",
  "A Type 1 diabetic teenager forgets to take his insulin before eating a large pizza. Three hours later, he is vomiting, breathing rapidly (Kussmaul respiration), and his breath smells fruity. His blood glucose reads 450 mg/dL. His mother calls 911. Explain the biochemical cascade that led to diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), and how does this illustrate the role of insulin in everyday metabolism?": "",
  "Diabetic ketoacidosis biochemistry: (1) Trigger: no insulin + carbohydrate load. Insulin normally: ↑GLUT4 translocation → ↑glucose uptake by muscle/adipose; ↑glycogenesis; ↑glycolysis/lipogenesis; ↓lipolysis; ↓gluconeogenesis; ↓ketogenesis. Without insulin: the metabolic opposite. (2) Hyperglycemia: glucose can't enter cells (except brain, liver, RBCs — insulin-independent GLUT transporters) → blood glucose rises. Liver: ↑gluconeogenesis (amino acids, glycerol → glucose) + ↑glycogenolysis → even higher blood glucose. Above renal threshold (~180 mg/dL) → osmotic diuresis (glucosuria) → dehydration, electrolyte loss (Na⁺, K⁺). (3) Ketogenesis: without insulin, hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose is fully active → ↑↑↑ lipolysis → massive free fatty acid release → liver β-oxidation → excess acetyl-CoA. Citric acid cycle overwhelmed (OAA depleted for gluconeogenesis) → acetyl-CoA → ketone bodies: acetoacetate, β-hydroxybutyrate (strong acids), acetone (volatile → fruity breath). (4) Metabolic acidosis: ketone accumulation → pH drops < 7.35 (normal: 7.35-7.45). Bicarbonate buffer exhausted. Compensatory: Kussmaul breathing (deep, rapid) → blow off CO₂ → attempt to raise pH. (5) Treatment: IV insulin (drives glucose into cells, stops ketogenesis), IV fluids (correct dehydration — average deficit 5-7L), electrolyte replacement (especially K⁺ — insulin drives K⁺ into cells → hypokalemia risk → cardiac arrhythmia). (6) Mortality: untreated DKA was uniformly fatal before insulin discovery (Banting & Best, 1921). With treatment, mortality ~1-5% (higher in developing countries).": "",
  "A dermatologist explains to a patient with severe sunburn that UV-B radiation caused the formation of thymine dimers in the DNA of her skin cells, and that her repair enzymes are working to fix the damage. The patient asks why this matters. Using your knowledge of everyday biochemistry, explain how UV damage, DNA repair, and antioxidants relate to skin cancer risk.": "",
  "UV damage and skin cancer biochemistry: (1) UV-B (280-315 nm) directly absorbed by DNA bases → adjacent pyrimidines form covalent bonds: cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers (CPDs, most common: T=T, T=C) and 6-4 photoproducts. (2) Repair: nucleotide excision repair (NER) — a multi-enzyme system that recognizes bulky DNA distortions, excises ~24-32 nucleotides around the damage, and resynthesizes using the undamaged strand as template. In humans, ~10 proteins involved (XPA through XPG). Xeroderma pigmentosum (XP): autosomal recessive mutations in NER genes → inability to repair UV damage → 1,000× increased skin cancer risk → patients must avoid all sunlight. (3) Mutation signature: if unrepaired CPD is replicated → DNA polymerase inserts adenine opposite the dimer → C→T or CC→TT transitions. p53 tumor suppressor gene frequently mutated in skin cancers — specific 'UV signature' mutations confirm UV as causative. (4) UV-A (315-400 nm, penetrates deeper) → primarily indirect damage: generates ROS (singlet oxygen, superoxide) → oxidative DNA damage (8-oxoguanine), lipid peroxidation, protein oxidation. Antioxidants (vitamin C, E, polyphenols from green tea/berries) can neutralize these ROS. (5) Skin cancer statistics: most common cancer globally. Basal cell carcinoma (most common, rarely metastatic), squamous cell carcinoma, melanoma (deadliest — ~8,000 deaths/year in US). UV exposure is primary modifiable risk factor. (6) Sunscreen biochemistry: mineral/physical sunscreens (zinc oxide, titanium dioxide) reflect UV; chemical sunscreens (oxybenzone, avobenzone) absorb UV and dissipate as heat.": "紫外线损害和皮肤癌生物化学:(1)紫外线-B(280-315纳米)直接被DNA基地吸收的紫外线(UV-B)(280-315纳米)和皮肤生物化学:(1)紫外线-B(280-B)直接被DNA基地吸收的紫外线(UV-B)(280-315纳米)形成相邻的粘合性粘合性粘结:环丁烷丙胺(CPD,最常见的是:T=T,T=C=C)和6-4光制品。 (2)修理:核脑切除修补(NER)——一个多酶系统,它能识别大宗DNA扭曲,在损害周围切除,以及利用未损坏的直径的直线(24-32纳基)核离子(DNA聚合物),在普通的血红外线(NC-4)中插入了直径直线(X)的亚内核电离子(VIII-氧)的亚丁基内基内核电化学接触(V."
}